Looking back at the ClassUtils.java code I read earlier, I found the `toClass` method at the end:

```java
public static Class<?>[] toClass(Object[] array) {
    if (array == null) {
        return null;
    } else if (array.length == 0) {
        return ArrayUtils.EMPTY_CLASS_ARRAY;
    }
    Class<?>[] classes = new Class[array.length];
    for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
        classes[i] = array[i].getClass();
    }
    return classes;
}
```

The problem is in the loop `classes[i] = array[i].getClass();`. When `array[i]` is `null`, calling `array[i].getClass()` will throw a `NullPointerException`.

The test expects that `ClassUtils.toClass(new Object[] { "Test", null, 99d })` should return `new Class[] { String.class, null, Double.class }`, where the null element produces a `null` class instead of throwing an exception.

Let me fix this by updating the `toClass` method to handle null values properly:

