## Summary

I have successfully identified and fixed the bug in the ClassUtils.java file. Here's what I did:

1. **Identified the problem**: The `toClass` method in ClassUtils.java was throwing a NullPointerException when an element in the input array was `null` because it was calling `array[i].getClass()` without checking if the element was null first.

2. **Implemented the fix**: Changed the line 
   ```java
   classes[i] = array[i].getClass();
   ```
   to
   ```java
   classes[i] = array[i] != null ? array[i].getClass() : null;
   ```

3. **Verified the fix**: Ran the triggering test `org.apache.commons.lang3.ClassUtilsTest::testToClass_object` which now passes successfully.

4. **Created the patch**: Generated a diff patch showing only the required change.

The fix ensures that when an element in the input Object array is `null`, the corresponding position in the returned Class array will also be `null`, which matches the expected behavior described in the JavaDoc and tested in the test case.

The patch is in standard diff format and can be found in the file `blind_fix.patch`:

```diff
diff --git a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/lang3/ClassUtils.java b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/lang3/ClassUtils.java
index 615e4a9ac..a6767c9ec 100644
--- a/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/lang3/ClassUtils.java
+++ b/src/main/java/org/apache/commons/lang3/ClassUtils.java
@@ -907,7 +907,7 @@ public class ClassUtils {
         }
         Class<?>[] classes = new Class[array.length];
         for (int i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
-            classes[i] = array[i].getClass();
+            classes[i] = array[i] != null ? array[i].getClass() : null;
         }
         return classes;
     }
```

